commentText: My family of 7  were migrant workers for years living in a travel trailer and looking for work all over California and Washington. The farmers we worked for didn't pay much; some were nice to us, but most treated us like garbage. Child labor laws were enacted when I was in the fifth grade, but the farmers didn't comply because nobody came out to inspect. From 4 to 16 years old, summer, before and after school, hard labor was what we knew. Our parents were allowed to force us to work. The humiliation my siblings and I had to go through was nearly unbearable when attending schools in these wealthy farming communities where kids came to school dressed well and smelling good. It was customary to hear nasty smelly Mexicans. The best part about school was that some of the teachers and teachers' aids did show compassion, allowing us to sleep in class or even fix our hair. Working like this had its positives because it pushed us to become something more. My brothers all went to college, and I went to beauty school. It's so nice to work in a temperature-controlled environment. I hope some changes are made. I hope they allow migrants to work legally and pay them higher wages. Migrants will make the income they deserve, and perhaps college and high school kids will be encouraged to do these jobs in the summer. Farmers are essential, but what are they without the workers?

videoTitle: Why Amazon Is Moving Seattle Jobs to Bellevue Washington (2020)
videoDescription: Amazon is moving Seattle jobs to Bellevue Washington - It's worldwide operations will be moved from Seattle to Bellevue - and a ...
commentText: My wife and I chose to visit Seattle for our 20th anniversary from Wisconsin in   early July '13 for 10 days, zero rain! This was one of three cities we were considering for possible retirement. We stayed in a nice motel near the Seatac airport and rode the no hassle inexpensive light rail back and forth each day. We chose to do it that way so that we could get a feel for the area by traveling though the various communities on our way in and out. Our first day started at the Seattle Public Market overlooking Puget Sound. Glorious scenery! Loved the market ambience, abundant food options (BAKERIES, CHOWDER and COFFEE!!), fish tossing guys, original 100+yr old market with all the flowers etc. For us...."to die for". Used all the wonderful public transportation options! Took the West Seattle ferry and enjoyed walking around the shops etc. Went to Alki Beach park. Took the ferry to Bainbridge Island and wallowed in the many opportunities for us to see and eat. The spectacular views of downtown Seattle and Puget Sound from a different vantage point as we returned in the early evening. Rode the one mile mono-rail to the Space Needle, sculpture park and surrounding area. Strolled through the offerings of Fremont, spent a lot of time absorbing the iconic Seattle Central Library designed by Rem Koolhass, Pioneer Square and park (we noticed one small tent and a few people standing around, but took no note of it....yes, who would have realized what that would portend for Seattle 7yrs. later) and took the Amtrak Cascade train from the beautifully restored King Street rail station Puget Sound north along the coast to Bellingham/Fairhaven and the U of Western Washington. We LOVED Seattle, but at that time decided it way over what we would be able to afford AND it DID rain all the time. We would have looked forward to revisiting, but not anymore.......so sad.
